The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, July 30, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, July 29: The rupee today slumped to a 13-month closing low of 46.47 per dollar, pulled down by sustained month-end dollar demand. On the back of yesterdays 10 paise decline, the rupee lost yet another whopping 15 paise from Wednesdays close of 46.32. Nervousness continued to grip the forex market as global demand for dollars fuelled amid thinning supplies due to a slowdown in foreign fund inflows, dealers said. Soaring crude prices also weighed heavily on the rupee value, they added.																								 Mumbai, July 29: The Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi) has recommended certain disclosures, including the risk factors and financial information, for overseas bodies such as companies planning to raise resources from the domestic markets through Indian depository receipts.																								 Mumbai, July 29: Toyota Kirloskar Motor, a joint venture between Toyota Motor Corporation and the Kirloskar group, is planning to increase its production capacity at the Bidadi plant in Bangalore to 60,000 units from the existing 45,000 units.																								 New Delhi, July 29: The government has clarified that the restoration of the duty entitlement passbook (DEPB) scheme benefits for the steel sector will be prospective in effect from July 12, 2004.																								 New Delhi, July 29: The Centre has appointed Wajahat Habibullah as the new textiles secretary.
